THE SEAL BROKE ON THAT DRUM AND 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED INTO THE TRAILER.  ABSORBENT WAS GENEROUSLY APPLIED TO THE SPILL AREA.  THE DRUM WAS UPRIGHTED AND REBRACED AND THE SEAL REPLACED.  ABSORBENT USED TO CLEAN THE SPILL WAS PLACED IN A BARRELL AND LEFT ON THE TRAILER FOR DISPOSAL AT THE RECEIVER.

column168: OUR UNIT TRAVELING EAST ON I-16 TRANSPORTING INTERMODAL TANKER WITH 5200 GALLONS OF NAPHTHENIC ACID FROM TUSCALOOSA, AL. TO THE GEORGIA STATE  PORT IN GARDEN CITY, GA.  AS UNIT PASSED UNDERNEATH OVERPASS NEAR DUBLIN, GA., PERSON OR PERSONS UNKNOWN DROPPED A LARGE ROCK FROM THE OVERPASS THROGH THE DRIVER'S WINDSHIELD ON THE TRUCK.  DRIVER THEN LOST CONTROL OF THE UNIT, OVERTURNING ON THE EAST SIDE OF I-16.  AS THE UNIT OVERTURNED, THE IMPACT WITH THE GROUND RIPPED OPEN THE RIGHT TOP CORNER OF THE INTERMODAL TANK, RESULTING IN THE LOSS OF CARGO.  DRIVER TREATED FOR SEVERE CUTS HEAD AND CHEST ALONG WITH MULTIPLE BRUISES AND LATER RELEASED FROM HOSPITAL.  A NUMBER OF AMBULANCE ATTENDANTS AND NURSES AT THE HOSPITAL COMPLAINED OF BEING MADE SICK FROM THE ODOR OF THE CARGO WHICH HAD SATURATED THE DRIVERS' CLOTHES.  NONE WERE HOSPITALIZED.  APPROXIMATELY 200 TONS OF SOIL WAS REMOVED FROM THE WRECK SITE, NEW TOP SOIL BROUGHT IN AND THE AREA WAS RESEEDED UNDER THE DIRECTION OF THE GA EPD.  WE EXPECT TO HAVE THE SOIL INCINERATED AFTER PROPER TESTING.  LAURENS COUNTY GEORGIA SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT IS HANDLING THIS INCIDENT AS A CRIMINAL CASE AND NOT AN ACCIDENT.

AT APPROXIMATELY 3:45 ON JUNE 25, 1993 A SPILL OCCURRED IN THE ROSS TRANSPORTATION SERVICES, INC TRANSFER STATION. THE RTS DRIVER DROPPED THE VAN OF DRUMS IN THE TRANSFER AREA AND DISCOVERED A LEAKING 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WHEN HE  OPENED THE DOORS OF THE TRAILER.  APPROPRIATE PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY BY MOVING THE VAN ONTO CONTAINMENT AT THE PROCESS DOCK.  HOWEVER, APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS OF MATERIAL REACHED THE GROUND IN THE TRANSFER AREA.  THE SPILL WAS REPORTABLE FOR IGNITABLITY. RIS PERSONNEL OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUM AND CLEANED UP THE VISUALLY CONTAMINATED SOIL AND GRAVEL AND PLACED IT INTO A 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM.  ALL SEVEN DRUMS OF THE CUSTOMER'S MATERIAL AND THE SPILL CLEAN-UP MATERIAL WERE TAKEN TO THE INCINERATOR TO BE PROCESSED AS SOON AS POSSIBLE. THE SPILL OCCURRED DUE TO A PIN HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  THE CUSTOMER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND REMINDED TO CHECK EACH DRUM'S INTEGRITY PRIOR TO SHIPMENT.  THE RTS MANAGER REVIEWED WITH THE DRIVER DOT AND RIS DRUM CONDITION REQUIREMENTS FOR WHICH EACH DRUM IS TO BE INSPECTED PRIOR TO LOADING.

A 5 GALLON STEEL PAIL WAS FOUND LEAKING UPON ARRIVAL.  THE PAIL WAS ISOLATED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAY.  ABSORBANT MATERIAL WAS USED TO CLEAN UP THE SIPLLAGE.  THE DAMAGED PAIL AND ABSORBANT MATERIAL WERE PLACED IN A NEW D.O.T. APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM, WITH PROPER MARKINGS AND LABELS APPLIED.  THE SALVAGE PAIL AND THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT WERE FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

A CITY DRIVER WAS OPENING TRAILER DOOR AND SMELLED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM A PLASTIC DRUM.  DRIVER HAD JUST PICKED UP THE SHIPMENT FROM THE SHIPPER'S DOCK. THE SHIPPER WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT. THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED FOR ASSISTANCE.  A CERTIFIED RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  ONE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING AND WAS PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED INTO A NEW DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM, WITH PROPER MARKINGS AND LABELS APPLIED.  THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED UP AND THE SPILLAGE WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF BY A HAZARDOUS WASTE COMPANY.  THE SALVAGE DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR CLAIM CREDIT.

THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN FORWARDED ON TO DESTINATION.

DRIVER STOPPED AT TOLARAM FIBER'S ENTRANCE GATE.  WHEN HE STOPPED, THE DRUM DOLLY CONTAINED WITHIN THE TRAILER ROLLED FORWARD AND PUNCTURED THE DRUM OF PERCLENE FG. column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: A CUBIC YARD DOT-E 10273 FIBER BOX WAS LOADED WITH WHAT WAS OBSERVED TO BE A DRY CHROMIUM SLUDGE WASTE.  EN ROUTE, IT WAS DISCOVERED  THAT RESIDUAL LIQUID THAT WAS NOT VISIBLE AT THE TIME THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED, SEPARATED FROM THE MATERIAL WHERE IT COLLECTED IN THE LOWER CORNER OF THE CONTAINER.  THE LIQUID ESCAPED THE INNER LINING THROUGH A SMALL TEAR THAT WAS CAUSED BY A NAIL USED TO SECURE THE FIBER BOX TO THE PALLET. APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE IDENTIFIED THIS SITUATION DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBOR'S ALBANY SERVICE CENTER.  PERSONNEL FROM THE SERVICE CENTER ALONG WITH THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED THE FREE LIQUID AND TRANSFERRED THE CONTENTS OF THE CONTAINER INTO A NEW DOT-E 10273 BOX. ALLL CLEAN-UP MATERIAL AND DEBRIS WERE PLACED IN THE NEW CONTAINER AND SENT TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY IDENTIFIED ON THE SHIPPING PAPER FOR DISPOSAL.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS SITUATION, PERSONNEL RESPONSIBLE FOR LOADING THIS TYPE OF CONTAINER HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT THE CONTAINERS FOR ANY SHARP OBJECTS THAT COULD JEOPARDIZE THE CONTAINER'S INTEGRITY PRIOR TO THE INITIATION OF LOADING PROCEDURES.  IN ADDITION, EACH LOAD MUST BE INSPECTED FOR EVIDENCE OF ANY RESIDUAL LIQUID. IN EVENT RESIDUAL LIQUID IS IDENTIFIED OR SUSPECTED, THE MATERIAL IS TO BE RECONTAINERIZED  INTO SUITABLE CONTAINERS PRIOR TO TRANSPORATION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO NEGOTIATE AN S-CURVE. DRIVER STATED HE MADE IT OK THROUGH THE FIRST RIGHT HAND CURVE, BUT WHILE TRYING TO GO THROUGH THE SECOND PART, A LEFT HAND CURVE, HE FELT TRANSPORT STARTING TO LEAN TO THE RIGHT.  DRIVER STATED HE KEPT TRYING TO PULL UNIT BACK STRAIGHT, BUT HE COULDN'T.  THE TRANSPORT ROLLED OVER ONTO ITS TOP RUPTURING THE TOP RIGHT SIDE OF TRAILER.  THIS ALLOWED THE PRODCUT TO ESCAPE.  NRC REPORT#179967 CLEAN UP WAS HANDLED BY WEAVERTOWN ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP.

PROPER FITTINGS WERE NOT BROUGHT FOR THE LOADING OF THE ANTI FREEZE. DIFFERENT SIZE FITTINGS WERE USED TO CONNECT THE HOSE THAT DID NOT SUPPORT THE HOSE PROPERLY.  THE WEIGHT FROM THE HOSE CAUSED THE FITTINGS TO LEAK.

AS THIS CAR WAS BEING PULLED FROM THE INDUSTRY LOADING SPOT, ACROSS THE SWITCH, AND ONTO RAILROAD PROPERTY.  THE PRODUCT SPLASHED FROM AN APPARANT BROKEN SPRING SAFETY RELIEF DEVICE.  THE BRAKEMAN ON THE GROUND WAS SPLASHED WITH A VERY MINOR AMOUNT OF THE PRODUCT.  THE FIRE DEPT.  WAS CALLED AND THEY DECONTAMINATED THE BRAKEMAN AND TOOK HIM INTO THE HOSPITAL.  HE WAS GIVEN FIRST AID ONLY, AND ALLOWED TO RETURN TO WORK, IMMEDIATELY.  IN THE MEANTIME THE OTHER MEMBERS OF THE CREW HAD MOVED THE CAR THE SHORT DISTANCE BACK INTO THE INDUSTRY SPOT, FROM WHICH IT HAD JUST CAME, AND NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER THAT THERE WAS AN APPARENTLY DEFECTIVE SRV ON THE CAR AND IT WAS BEING REJECTED UNTIL SUCH TIME REPAIRS COULD BE MADE.

column42: CHARCOAL BRIQUETTES, SHELL, SCREENINGS, WOOD, ETC.
column168: THIS TRAILER WAS DISCOVERED SMOKING AT THE LOS ANGELES T.O.F.C. RAMP.  THE FIRE DEPT. PUT THE FIRE OUT AND THEIR INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE FIRE WAS CAUSED FROM THE LADING PACKAGED WHILE STILL HOT FROM THE MANUFACTURE PROCESS, RESULTING SPONTANEOUS COMBUSTION WITHIN THE TRAILER.  WE WERE UNABLE TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER BECAUSE THE NUMBER USED THE WAYBILL FOR EMERGENCY CONTACT WAS THAT OF CHEMTREC, AND THE SHIPPER MARK VII TRANSPORTION IS NOT A MEMBER OF CHEMTREC.  THE REMAINING (UNBURNED) BAGS OF CHARCOAL WERE REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER, STACKED ON THE GROUND ONLY 1 LEVEL HIGH, AND ALLOWED TO COOL BEFORE MOVING TO DESTINATION.  THE DAMAGE TO THE TRAILER WAS CONSIDERED MINOR AT APPX. $900. THE RESIDUE OF THE UNBURNED CHARCOAL WAS PLACED IN A DISPOSAL RCEPTICLE WHEN THE COOLING PROCESS WAS COMPLETE.

LOADERS AND DRIVERS WILL BE INSTRUCTED TO POSITION THE LOADBAR SO THAT THE LOAD LOCK IS TURNED AWAY FROM CONTAINERS. column168: ALTHOUGH PROPERLY PACKAGED, THIS WAS DAMAGED BY A "TUG" OPERATED BY A FEDERAL EXPRESS EMPLOYEE.  THE INSPECTION AFTERWARD DETERMINED THE INNER CAN WAS DAMAGED AT THE CLOSURE. WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER 3 PACKAGES EXACTLY ALIKE WERE DISCOVERED LEAKING.  EACH WAS PLACEDIN A SPILL TRAY AND TAKEN TO THE PACKAGE SERVICE CENTER.  UPON INSPECTION EACH OF THESE THREE PACKAGES WERE FOUND TO BE VERY POORLY PACKED METAL ONE GALLON PAINT CAN HAD NO CLIPS AD THERE WERE NO PARTITIONS BETWEEN CANS AND NO CUSHIONING INSIDE PACKAGE.   OUT OF THE THREE PACKAGES EACH CONTAINING 4-1 GALLON CANS (TOTAL OF 12 GALLONS) 5 GALLONS OF ADHESIVE LEAKED OUT.  ENTIRE 5 GALLONS AND ALL CONTAMINATED CARDBOARD WERE DISPOSED OF WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.
PLEASE SEE ATTACHED

SHIPMENT WAS PICKED UP AT CURTIN MATHESON, WOODDALE, IL ON 6/15/93, AND CARTONS WERE LOOSE ON A PALLET WITH OTHER SHIPMENTS NEAR THE REAR OF THE TRAILE.  THE DRIVER FAILED TO PROPERLY SECURE HIS FREIGHT TO KEEP IT FROM MOVING, AND ONE CARTON FELL OFF THE PALLET, CAUSING ONE OF THE FOUR BOTTLES OF METHANOL TO BREAK.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE BOTTLE WERE LOST AND THE SPILLAGE WAS NOT DISCOVERED UNTIL THE TRAILER WAS PUT INTO THE DOCK FOR UNLOADING EARLY THE MORNING OF 6/16/93.  REIDEL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. WAS CALLED TO THE TERMINAL FOR CLEANUP AND DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE MATERIALS.  THE DRIVER HAS BEEN INFORMED OF HIS FAILURE AND A LETTER OF INFORMATION WILL BE PUT IN HIS FILE.

WHILE MAKING A ROUTINE SAFETY CHECK OF HIS EQUIPMENT AND CARGO, THE DRIVER DISCOVERED A LOSS OF PRODUCT INTO THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT SYSTEMS OF THE TRAILER.  HE CONTAINED THE SPILL WITH ABSORBENTS, PLACED THE DRUM AND PROCEEDED TO SAFETY KLEEN CORP. IN WILKES BARRE, PA WHERE THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS OVERPACKED AND THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS CLEANED.  ALL CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF AT THE CONSIGNEE (SAFETY KLEE- NEW CASTLE, KY). NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS LOST TO THE ENVIRONMENT OR ENTERED ANY DRAINS OR WATERWAYS.
DRIVER WAS PUMPING DIESEL FROM UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK ONTO TRAILIER. DRIVER THOUGHT HE HAD SHUT PUMP OFF AND HOSE BECAME DISENGAGED CAUSING SPILL OF DIESEL FUEL ONTO GROUND.

THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED WHILEUNLOADING A PACKAGE CAR.  ALL 12 BOTTLES WERE OUT OF THE CARTON LOOSE IN THE TOTE BOX.  LOOSE LID ON 1 OF THE 12 BOTTLES CAUSED DAMAGED, ENTIRE LIQUID SPILLED IN CARTON.  THE COMPLETE PARCEL WAS REPACKED ACCORDING TO UPS SPECIFICATIONS AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.  A DAMAGE REPORT AND ISP CARD PREPARED AND SENT TO ORIGIN DISTRICT FOR FOLLOW UP WITH THE SHIPPER.

column168: GSIX 150 WAS SITTING ON LEASE TRACKAGE IN TRACK #7, EAST BILLINGS YARD. SWITCH CREW MOVED INTO TRACK AND FOUND "A" END OF CAR EMITTING VAPOR WITH FROSTING PRESENT AT FAILED AREA.  THE VICINITY OF LEAK WAS ISOLATED AND RESPONSE AGENECIES CALLED.  UPON ARRIVAL PRESSURE WAS IMMEDIATELY REDUCED IN TANK BY TRANSLOADING PRODUCT TO ANOTHER RAIL CAR AND FLARING VAOR TO ATMOSPHERE, THE REMAINDER OF THE LIQUD WAS THEN TRANSLOADED TO A HIGHWAY TRANSPORT VESSEL BY COMPRESSOR AND THE REMAINDER OF THE VAPOR WAS FLARED OFF.  GSIX 150 THEN INDUCED WITH NITROGEN TO INERT REMAINING GAS. EXPLOSIVE METER READINGS TAKEN AND WHEN CAR WAS FREE OF VAPOR, TANK WAS FILLED WITH APPROXIMATELY 10,000 GALLONS OF WATER.  GSIX 150 HAS SINCE HAD FIBER OPTIC END SILL INSPECTION (REPORT AND DIAGRAM ENCLOSED) AND IS SCHEDULED TO BE TRANSPORTED ABOARD A FLAT CAR BY RAIL TO TRANSCISCO RAIL SERVIES FACILITY AT MILES CITY, MT.

DOME LID NOT TIGHTENED PROPERLY ALLOWING APPROX 5 GALS WASTE MINERAL SPIRITS TO SLOSH OUT TANKER WHEN DRIVING OFF PROPERTY.  SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND IMMEDIATLEY CLEANED UP USING ABSORBENT SHEETS.  DRIVER SAID HE WILL ALWAYS DOUBLE CHECK DOME LID BEFORE MOVING VEHICLE TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.

column168: FREIGHT HAD BEEN LOADED BY THE SHIPPER AT THE SHIPPER'S DOCK.  TRAILER WAS SEALED AND NOT HANDLED UNTIL ARRIVAL AT CONSIGNEE LOCATION. column168: WE LOADED 2500 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL AT YOUR DESIGNATED FACILITY TO BE DELIVERED TO THE COAST GUARD CUTTER LONG ISLAND AT THE USCG BASE IN SAN PEDRO.  WE ARRIVED FOR THE DELIVERY AT APPROXIMATELY 0900 HOURS.  THE LONG ISLAND ARRIVED AT 1200 HOURS AND TIED UP ALONG SIDE THE CONIFER.  OUR DRIVER FIRST BOARDED THE LONG ISLAND TO VERIFY WE HAD PROPER FITTINGS OUR DRIVER AND HOSEMAN THEN HOOKED THE HOSE LENGTHS TOGETHER ON THE DOCK.  THE DRIVER VERIFIED THAT THE CAMLOCKS WWERE IN GOOD CONDITION AND NOT WORN. SEAMEN FROM THE LONG ISLAND CAME OVER TO THE CONIFER AND HAD OUR DRIVER HAND THEM THE HOSE FROM THE DOCK; THE SEAMEN THEN TOOK THE HOSE ACROSS THE CONIFER AND THEN ONTO THE LONG ISLAND.  THE LONG ISLAND SEAMEN KEPT IN CONTACT VIA TWO-WAY RADIOS.  FINALLY, VIA THE RADIO, SEAMEN ON THE LONG ISLAND ADVISED THE LONG ISLAND SEAMAN ON THE DOCK THAT THE HOSE CONNECTION HAD BEEN MADE ON THE LONG ISLAND AND THAT THE DELIVERY COULD BEGIN.  OUR DRIVER ASKED IF ALL VALVES WERE PROPERLY OPEN AND LONG ISLAND SEAMEN ADVISED OUR DRIVER THAT THEY WERE.  OUR DRIVER THEN OPENED THE TRUCK VALVE ABOUT 25% AND THEN BEGAN A NORMAL GRAVITY (NO PUMP) DELIVERY AFTER DETEMINING THAT THERE WERE NO FITTING OR OTHER LEAKS.  OUR HOSEMAN WAS ON THE CONIFER WHERE HE COULD TALK WITH BOTH THE BENETO DRIVER ON THE DOCK AND THE SEAMAN ON THE LONG ISLAND.  ALL HOSE FITTINGS WERE ON THE CONIFER EXCEPT THE FINAL CONNECTION ON THE LONG ISLAND AND THE BEGINNING CONNECTION AT THE BENETO TRUCK.  AFTER ABOUT 5 MINUTES IT BECAME APPARENT THAT PRODUCT WAS EITHER NOT MOVING OR MOVING VERY SLOWLY.  OUR DRIVER AGAIN QUESTIONED THE LONG ISLAND SEAMAN ABOUT ALL VALVES BEING OPEN AND WAS ADVISED THAT THE VALVES WERE OPEN.  OUR DRIVER AND HOSEMAN THEN WENT ON TOP THE BENETO TRUCK, DETEMINED PRODUCT WAS NOT LEAVING THE TRUCK, AND AGAIN ASKED ABOUT POSSIBLY CLOSED VALVES.  ADVISED THEY WERE ALL OPEN, THE DRIVER DECIDED TO PUMP THE PRODUCT TO THE LONG ISLAND.  HOSE CONNECTIONS WERE CHANGED AS NECESSARY, THE HOSEMAN RETURNED TO THE CONIFER AND THE PUMP WAS SLOWLY ENGAGED.  AS EXPECTED, THE HOSE STIFFENED, BUT A FEW DROPS OF PRODUCT DRIPPED FROM THE HOSE CONNECTIONS ON THE CONIFER BECAUSE HE KNEW THE PRODUCT WOULD NOT DRAIN FROM THE HOSE INTO THE LONG ISLAND, REQUESTED THE RESPONSIBLE SEAMAN FROM THE LONG ISLAND COME OVER TO THE CONIFER PUMPING IT BACK INTO THE TRUCK.  THIS NOT-UNUSUAL PROCEDURE IS ACCOMPLISHED BY SLOWLY CRACKING ONE OF THE CAMLOCKS AT THE CONNECTION POINT (IN THIS CASE ON THE LONG ISLAND), ALLOWING SOME AIR TO ENTER THE HOSE THEREBY PREMITTING THE PRODUCT TO BE PUMPED BACK INTO THE TRUCK.  THE SEAMAN WAS TOLD THAT IF THERE WAS ANY MINOR LEAKAGE TO SHUT THE CAMLOCK IMMEDIATELY.  HE WAS TOLD THAT THE DRIVER WOULD BEGIN THE PUMP, WOULD SIGNAL THE HOSEMAN THAT THE CAMLOCK SHOULD BE CRACKED AND THAT THE SEAMAN SHOULD WATCH THE HOSEMAN FOR THE SIGNAL TO CRACK THE CAMLOCK (THIS WAS NECESSARY BECAUSE THE DRIVER COULD NOT SEE THE SEAMAN AT THE CONNECTION POINT AND THE USCG PERSONNEL WITH TWO-WA

A PACKAGE SHIPPED BY PRIMROSE OIL CO OF DALLAS TEXAS ARRIVED AT THE LENEXA HUB VIA GROUND TRAILER.  THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED AND WAS SORTED USING NORMAL METHODS.  SEVERAL PACKAGES THAT WERE SORTED TO THE SAME CONVEYOR BELT WERE INVOLVED IN TWO JAMS.  IT IS THOUGHT THE PACKAGE FROM PRIMROSE OIL WAS INVOLVED IN BOTH.  IN EACH CASE, AN EMPLOYEE PROCEEDED TO FREE THE PACKAGES THAT WERE STUCK, IT WAS AT THIS TIME THAT THE SAME EMPLOYEES NOTICED A STRONG ODOR.  THE PACKAGE BEGAN SPILLING ITS CONTENTS ON THE GREEN BELT JUST AFTER IT EXITED A SLIDE.  THE BELT WAS SHUT OFF AS THE ODOR BECAME STRONGER.  EMPLOYEES IN THE AREA WERE MOVED AWAY FROM THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND THE FIRST RESPONDER EMPLOYEES WERE CALLED IN TO EXAMINE THE PACKAGE.  THE BUILDING WAS EVACUATED AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND EMERGENCY CREWS WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE.  A HAZMAT CLEAN-UP CREW SECURED THE AREA.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND UPS FACILITY WAS CLEANED UP BY THE HAZMAT CREWS.  THE PACKAGING AND REMAINING CONTENTS OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL WERE SECURED IN THE DMP BARRELS.

column168: I WAS CALLED AT 2300 PM AND ADVISED THAT WE HAD A PACKAGE LEAKING THAT WAS IN A DOT E 9168 PACKAGING. I ADVISED THEM TO SECURE THE AREA AND START SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES.  I CALLED PAT OPPENHEIMER AND ADVISED OF THE SPILL.  HE TOLD ME TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER IF POSSIBLE.  I WENT AHEAD AND TOLD THE SPECIALIST TO CLEAN THE SPILL UP WHICH AT THIS TIME WAS A NOTICEABLE STAIN ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX. I CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND TOLD HIM WHAT I HAD AND TOLD HIM THAT I WOULD BE HOLDING THE PACKAGE FOR DISPOSITION UNTIL THE INFORMATION GATHERED ON THE SUBSTANCE SPILLED COULD BE ASCERTAINED. AFTER SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED I CALLED THE SPECIALIST BACK TO SEE HOW THE PACKAGE WAS ON THE INSIDE.  HE EXPLAINED THAT WHEN HE OPENED THE PACKAGE FOR INSPECTION THIS IS WHAT HE FOUND. HE FOUND THE APPROPRIATE CUSHIONING AND PACKING MATERIALS, SEALED PLASTIC BAG WITH A METAL CAN INSIDE THE BAG. WHEN HE CHECKED THE BAG HE COULD TELL THAT THE CAN LOOKED LIKE IT HAD EXPLODED FROM THE INSIDE OUT AND THERE WAS A LIQUID SUBSTANCE COMING OUT OF THE CAN. IT WAS AT THIS POINT THAT I TOLD THE SPECIALIST TO PLACE EVERYTHING IN SALVAGE DRUMS AND DO NOT REOPEN UNTIL FURTHER NOTICE. ATTACHMENTS INCLUDE: SHIPPING PAPERS, COPY OF MSDS, AND INTRACOMPANY CORRESPONDENCE.

UPON AN INSPECTION AT A DOT ROADSIDE INSPECTION FACILITY IN LOGAN, IOWA ON JUNE 29, 1993, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A FLANGE GASKET WAS DEFECTIVE.  AS A RESULT, THE POTENTIAL EXISTED FOR THE ACID CONTENTS TO LEAK.  ALTHOUGH A TRACE AMOUNT OF ACID WAS DETECTED ON THE GASKET ITSELF, THERE WAS, TO LAYNE'S KNOWLEDGE, NO ACTUAL LEAKAGE OR RELEASE OF ANY ACID ON TO THE GROUND SURFACE.  TO REMEDY THE SITUATION, THE SUBJECT CARGO TANK WAS DISPOSED OF BY LAYNE ON OR BEFORE AUGUST 6, 1993.

column168: ON JUNE 2, 1993, AT APPROX 11:30AM LAYNE WAS TRANSPORTING A PORTABLE TANKER CARRYING HYDROCHLORIC ACID ON INTERSTATE 255 IN ST LOUIS, MISSOURI, WHEN THE TANKER LEAKED APPROX 250 GALLONS OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  THE LEAK WAS CAUSED AS A RESULT OF THE FAILURE OF PVC NIPPLE NEAR THE CONTROL VALVE. UPON DISCOVERY OF THE LEAK, APPROPRIATE AUTHORITIES WERE CONTACTED AND THE ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH.  IN ADDITION, AN EARTHEN CONTAINMENT SYSTEM WAS CREATED TO STOP ANY FURTHER MIGRATION OF THE ACID. THE SPILL WAS THEN CLEANED UP, REMOVED AND DISPOSED OF PURSUANT TO APPLICABLE REGULATION.  LAYNE HAS REPAIRED THE DEFECTIVE PVC AND WILL INSURE THAT ALL CARGO TANKS ARE INSPECTED PRIOR TO EACH TRIP IN ORDER TO PREVENT SIMILAR OCCURRENCES IN THE FUTURE. COPY OF HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST IS ATTACHED.

column168: OUR FIELD SERVICE OPERATOR WAS FUELING A PICK UP TRUCK WHEN HE NOTICED SURGING THROUGH THE NOZZLE OF THE FUEL HOSE. HE GRABBED THE NOZZLE TO RELEASE THE AUTOMATIC TRIP LEVER AND SHUT OFF FUEL.  AN ESTIMATED FIVE GALLONS WAS SPILLED.  CORRECTIVE ACTION: REPLACE NOZZLE AND INSPECT OLD NOZZLE FOR DEFECTS, TOLD EMPLOYEE NOT TO USE AUTOMATIC FILL LEVER WHEN THEY LEAVE THE NOZZLE AND ADDED FUEL NOZZLE TO PRETRIP INSPECTIONS.

ON 6-2-93 AT 02:35, HAZMAT SPECIALIST, RANDY WILLIAMS, REPORTED A SHIPMENT AT THE HAZMAT SORT THAT WAS EMITTING AN ODOR.  AT 02:40, HAZMAT COORDINATOR, TONY FRYE, AND HAZMAT SPECIALIST JON MOOTS, ARRIVED AT THE HAZMAT SORT.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE, WE OBSERVED THE SHIPMENT SETTING OUTSIDE THE HAZMAT SORT IN A SECURED AREA.  JON DONNED STRUCTURAL FIRE FIGHTING GEAR AND AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE MASK TO INVESTIGATE THE SHIPMENT THAT WAS EMITTING THE ODOR.  THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS MARKED WITH FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS LABEL.  JON OPENED THE FIBERBOARD BOX AND INSIDE THERE WERE 3 1-GALLON METAL RECEPTICLES WITH CREW-TYPE CLOSURES. ALSO THERE WAS A 1-QUART METAL RECEPTICLE WITH A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE.  THERE WAS A MEANS TO SECURE THE CREW-TYPE CLOSURES.  INSIDE THE SCREW-TYPE COSURES WERE FRICTION-TYPE CLOSURES.  THIS IS WHERE THE LEAK OCCURRED.  THESE METAL RECEPTICLES WERE ALL PACKED IN PLASTIC BAGS.  THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX WAS MARKED "FUEL, AVIATION, TUBINE ENGINE, UN1863." THIS SHIPMENT WAS TENDERED ACCORDING TO THE IATA REGULATIONS.  THERE WAS NO SPECIFICATION MARKINGS FOR THIS SHIPMENT AND THERE WAS NO "CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY" LABELS ON THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND WILL BE FORWARDED ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

column17: HUNT J B SPECIAL COMMODITIES I
column168: THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED ON I-49 JUST NORTH OF LAFAYETTE, LA., ON JUNE 2ND. MICHAEL ROBERTSON, OUR DRIVER, STATED THAT HE HAD INSPECTED HIS LOAD WHILE AT A TRUCK STOP IN LAFAYETT, LA. AND ALL WAS FINE.  AFTER LEAVING, THE TRUCK STOP, A LOUISIANA STATE POLICE OFFICER NOTICED MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND STOPPED MR. ROBERTSON.  AFTER STOPPING, MR. ROBERTSON PLACED AN OVERPACKE DRU, NORMALLY CARRIED UNDER OUT TRAILER, AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER TO CATCH THE MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE TRIALER. THE OFFICER WOULD NOT LET OUR DRIVER, OPEN THE DOOR OR ENTER THE TRAILER. MR. ROBERTSON THEN CALLED AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO ME.  AN OFFICER AT THE SCENE GAVE ME INFORMATION APPEARING ON THE MANIFESTS.  THERE WERE DIVISIONS 3, 6.1, 8, 9, CARRIED ON THIS LOAD.  I WAS NOT GIVEN ENOUGH INFORMATION TO DETERMINE IF A REPORTABLE QUANTITY HAD BEEN RELEASED, AS THE SOURCE AND MATERIAL WAS NOT KNOW AT THAT TIME.  I IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED A RESPONSE CREW FROM CROWLEY LA TO RESPOND ON OUR BEHALF TO THE SCENE TO EFFECT CLEAN UP OPERATIONS.  I ADVISED OUR DRIVER TO NOTIFY ME IMMEDIATLEY UPON THE DISCOVERY OF THE EXACT MATERIAL THAT HAD BEEN SPILLED SO AS THE DETERMINE IF A REPORTABLE QUANTITY HAD BEEN RELEASED.  THE LAFAYETTE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZ-MAT TEAM WAS CALLED OUT TO DETEMINE THE NATURE, EXTENT AND CAUSE OF THE SPILL.  AFTER ENTERING THE TRAILER, THE HAZ-MAT TEAM FOUND THAT THE DRUM DOLLY HAD LID FORWARD AND PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF ONE DRUM. THE LEAKING DRUM CONTAINED "HAZARDOUS WASTE LIQUID, NOS, 3 PGIII UN1993 (METHYL ETHYL KETONE, TOLUNE).  NO REPORTABLE QUANTITIES WERE INVOLVED IN THIS SPILL.  THE CLEAN UP CREW RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND PROMPTLY CLEANED THE SPILLED MATERIAL FROM THE GROUND AND INSIDE OF THE TRAILER.  THE DAMGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO THE OVERPACK ALONG WITH THE ABSORBENT MATERIALS USED.  THE OVERPACKE THEN ACCOMPANIED THE REMAINDER TO THE ORIGINAL T.S.D. FACILITY DESTINATION, RENECO IN BENTON, AR.  ALTHOUGH ALL VAN TRAILERS OPERATED BY J.B. HUNT SPECIAL COMMODITIESARE SPECIALLY EQUIPPED WITH SPILL CONTAINMENT PANS, THIS WAS NOT EFFECTIVE DUE TO A TEAR IN THE REAR FLAP.  OUR TRAILERS ARE CURRENTLY BEING RETROFITTED WITH A DIFFERENT DESIGN REAR SEAL THAT DOES NOT USE A RUBBER FLAP.  WE FELL THAT THIS NEW DESIGN WILL BE SUPERIOR TO THE FLAP ARRANGEMENT, WHICH DID NOT HOLD UP WELL IN ROUGH USE.  THE DRUM DOLLY IS TO CARRIED IN A RACK UNDER THE TRAILER DESIGNED FOR THIS PURPOSE.  THE DRIVER WAS SEVERELY REPRIMANDED FOR NOT SECURING THE DRUM DOLLY AND ALLOWING THIS TO HAPPEN. ALL OTHER DRIVERS HAVE BEEN WARNED OF THE DANGER OF NOT SECURING THE DRUM DOLLY AS WELL.

WHILE UNLOADING THE DRUMS THAT WERE LOADED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER, THE ASSOCIATE DISCOVERED A LEAK.  THE CONSIGNEE WAS CALLED (ELF ATOCHEM NORTH AMERICA, HIGHWAY 1523, CALVERT CITY, KY.) AND THEY SENT THREE MEMBERS OF THEIR IN-HOUSE HAZMAT EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM TO OUR MAYFIELD TERMINAL TO OVERPACK THE LEAKING DRUM AND DECONTAMINATE OUR TRAILER.  THE RESPONSE TEAM TRANSPORTED THE OVERPACKED CONTAINER TO THE PLANT FOR PROPER REUSE AND/ OR DISPOSAL.  FIVE ASSOCIATES HAD WORKED IN THE TRAILER PRIOR TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE LEAK AND WERE TAKEN TO A LOCAL CLINCIC.  THEY WERE EXAMINED AND RELEASED TO FULL DUTIES THAT SAME DAY WITH NO FURTHER COMPLICATIONS.  THE RELEASE WAS REPORTED TO THE LEPC (SUSIE ETHRIDGE (502)527-1333), STATE DES (JOSEPH SCHMIDT (502) 564-2380), AND THE EPA (DAVID ADKINSON (502)564-7815).

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0219, NORTH LITTLE ROCK HUMP PERSONAL NOTED STRONG AMMONIA ODOR.  MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY (MCTS) WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MCTS HILL'S INSPECTION REVEALED VAPORS BY PASSING SAFETY RELIEF VALVE, CAR WAS ISOLATED. SHIPPER RESPONDED BY SENDING TRUCK WITH TRAILER OF WATER TO SCRUB VAPOR THROUGH IN ORDER TO REDUCE 175 LBS, OF TANK PRESSURE TO 0 LBS. OF PRESSURE.  A TWO INCH HOSE WAS USED FROM TANK CAR VAPOR VALVE TO TRUCK.  THE PRESSURE WAS REDUCED TO 0 IN THREE HOURS WITH NO ODORS FROM OPENING OF TRUCK MANWAY. ON MONDAY, JUNE 14TH, MANAGERS HILL AND LOW CHANGED THE "0" RINGS IN SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  ("0" RINGS WERE SCRAPED FROM RETAINER).  CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: ON 060893 AT APPROXIMATELY 930PM, REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM MANAGER TERMINAL OPERATIONS, JOHN RICE, THAT THE ABOVE CAR WAS SLOSHING LIQUID FROM THE TOP.  UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER NOTICED A STAIN ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR.  THE STAIN SEEMED TO ORIGINATE NEAR THE MANWAY COVER.  THE COVER WAS DAMP WITH PRODUCT.  REEDER CHECKED THE MANWAY BOLTS AND FOUND 3 THAT WERE NOT WRENCH TIGHT.  THE GASKET WAS BRITTLE.  REEDER MADE A NEW GASKET FROM GORE-TEX, LEAVING THE OLD GASKET IN PLACE.  THE COVER BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT WITHOUT DELAY. JIM COOPER OF CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) T. SMITH WAS NOTIFIED BY MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS (MTO) K. HUNT THAT GATX 15822 WAS LEAKING. UPON ARRIVAL, CHEMTREC (J. BOTWINICK) WAS NOTIFIED FOR SHIPPER CONTACT. DAVID JORNER FROM SHIPPER CONTACTED SSA/HM SMITH AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO TRANSLOAD THE CONTENTS FROM THE TANKCAR INTO HIGHWAY TANKS. UPON INSPECTION OF THE TANKCAR SMITH FOUND ONE REGULATOR VALVE CONTINUOUSLY OPERATING, RELEASING PRODUCT.  THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING WHERE THE VALVE MOUNTS TO THE MANWAY PRESSURE PLATE.  THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER WAS NOT SECURE DUE TO MISSING COVER BOLT.  CAR WAS BILLED TO SHOP FOR REPAIRS.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: ON 061893 AT APPROXIMATELY 5:30 P.M. A CAR INSPECTOR NOTICED THE ABOVE CAR LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  MTO LEHAN NOTIFIED REEDER.  UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER FOUND A STREAM OF LIQUID FLOWING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR. MOST OF THE LIQUID WAS EVAPORATING FROM THE SIDE BEFORE IT REACHED THE GROUND.  ON TOP OF THE CAR MANAGER REEDER FOUND LIQUID COMING FROM UNDER THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. HOECHST CELANESE SEAL #42611 WAS REMOVED AND THE HOUSING OPENED.  THE LIQUID WAS FLOWING FROM THE GASKET AREA BETWEEN THE LIQUID VALVE AND ITS MOUNTING FLANGE.  THE NUTS HOLDING THE LIQUID VALVE WERE TINGER TIGHT.  REEDER TIGHTENED ALL NUTS AND STOPPED THE LEAK.  A NEW SEAL MPRR 17 169077 WAS APPLIED.  CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED. THE CAR MOVED WITHOUT DELAY.

column168: ON TUESDAY, 6/15/93, TANK CAR GATX 12999 WAS ONE OF SEVERAL CARS THAT DERAILED AS PART OF UPRR TRAIN HOAD-14.  ALL CARS WERE UPRIGHT WITH WHEELS OFF ONLY.  THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF COMMODITY OR SIGNIFICANT DAMAGE AS A RESULT OF THE DERAILMENT. ON WEDNESDAY, 6/16/93, DURING THE RERAILING OPERATION, A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT BEGAN TO LEAK FROM BENEATH THE MANWAY COVER.  THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THIS SLOWED THE LEAKAGE SO THAT THE CAR COULD BE SAFELY RERAILED.  AFTER THE CAR WAS RERAILED FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE MANWAY GASKET WAS OLD AND WORN OUT. MR. JIM OSBURN, UPRR MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MAINTCE. CONTACTED MR. R. J. DEBATE OF AGRICO, THE CONSIGNEE, AND OBTAINED A NEW GASKET.  OSBURN INSTALLED THE NEW GASKET AND SECURED THE CAR FOR MOVEMENT. ADDITIONAL NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO MR. TIMOTHY BOLTON OF PHELPS DODGE MINING, THE SHIPPER.

column168: ON 6-17-93, SORT SUPERVISOR, BILL MINK, REPORTED A SHIPMENT THAT  WAS LEAKING AND EMITTING AN ODOR IN THE MAIN SORT.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE, I, TONY FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATIOR, AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST, JON MOOTS, INVESTIGATED THE SHIPMENT.  JON USED SOME PH PAPER TO CHECK THE SPILLED LIQUID MATERIAL.  THE PH PAPER TURNED RED.  THIS IS AN INDICATION OF AN ACID.  UPON OPENING THE FIBERBOARD BOX, HE FOUND INSIDE A SMALL ELECTRIC STORAGE BATTERY.  THIS BATTERY WAS LOADED AGAINST PROPER ORIENTATION IN THE FIBERBOX.  THERE WAS NO MEANS TO PROTECT THE BATTERY TERMINALS FROM SHORT CIRCUIT.  ALSO CONTAINED INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WERE TWO SMALL PLASTIC RECEPTICLES EACH CONTAINING HORTICULTURE SAND.  THERE WAS NEWSPAPER INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

S/A BALLANCE RESPONDED AND NOTED THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VLAVE LOOSE. VALVE WAS TIGHTENED.  THE CONTENTS REMAINING IN THE CAP WRE DRAINED OFF AND PLACED BACK INTO THE CONTAINER.  THE TANK CAR WAS RESIDUE CAR ONY.

D.C. COOPER, MANAGER, CTS, WHILE INSPECTING TANK CARS IN THE BMI COMPLEX, HENDERSON, NEVADA, OPENED THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER ON GATX14918, RESIDUE CHLORINE, AND LOCATED A VERY STRONG ODOR OF CHLORINE VAPOR.  THE RIGHT SIDE (WHEEL) VAPOR VALVE HAD THE ONE INCH PORT PLUG OUT AND LAYING ADJACENT TO THE VALVE.  THE WHEEL VALVE WAS CLOSED TIGHT.  THE PLUG WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE PORT AND TIGHTENED.  THE LEFT SIDE (WHEEL) VAPOR VALVE WAS NOT SECURED AND DEVELOPED TO BE THE SOURCE OF VAPOR LEAK.  THE SECURED AND DEVELOPED TO BE THE SOURCE OF THE VAPOR LEAK.  THE VALVE'S WHEEL HANDLE WAS FULLY TIGHTENED AND PROPERLY SECURED WITH ONE QUARTER TO ONE HALF TURN.  THE ONE INCH PORT PLUG WAS IN PLACE, HOWEVER, WAS ONLY FINGER TIGHT.  AFTER TIGHTENING THE VAPOR VALVE PROPERLY SECURING THE PORT PLUG, THE VAPOR LEAK CEASED.  INSPECTION OF THE LIQUID VALVES ALSO DEVELOPED THE PORT PLUGS TO BE THE FINGER TIGHT.  THE PORT PLUGS WERE PROPERLY SECURED.  THE ABOVE EXCEPTIONS WERE BROUGHT TO BE THE ATTENTION OF MR. DEAN SAYLOR, MANAGER OF SAFETY, PIONEEER CHLOR ALKALI, WHO STATED HE WOULD CONTACT THE SHIPPER AND DISCUSS PROPER SECUREMENT OF THE TANK CARS PRIOR TO RELEASING THEM FOR MOVEMENT.  THERE WERE NO OTHER NOTIFICATIONS MADE ON THIS INCIDENT ACCOUNT THE MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF LEAK.

CAR HAD BEEN INTERCHANGED FROM THE SANTE FE APPROXIMATELY 1 HOUR PRIOR TO DISCOVERY OF THE LEAK.  DUE TO THE LOCATION AND TYPE OF LEAK (WELD LEAKING), DECISION WAS MADE TO TRANLOAD PRODUCT.  A SECOND TANK CAR (NATX 29948) PULLED FROM THE SHIPPERS POOL.  THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSLOADED INTO NATX 29948.  THE CONSIGNEE WAS NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT AND TRANSFER.

INSPECTION DETERMINED THE FOLLOWING EXCEPTIONS;  1.  VACUUM RELIEF VALVE WAS FOUND TO BE HAND TIGHT AND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  VALVE REMOVED, TEFLON TAPE APPLIED TO VALVE THREADS AND VALVE SCREWED BACK INTO CAR.  VALVE TIGHTENED A PIPE WRENCH.  2. STANDARD GATX SAFETY VENT HOUSING COVER REMOVED (RUBBER, 3 BOLT PATTERN) AND FOUND THE RUPTURE DISK HAD FAILED AND THAT A THIN PIECE OF CARDBOARD (SHOE BOX TYPE) HAD BEEN WRAPPED IN CLEAR PLASTIC TAPE AND PLACED BETWEEN THE DISK AND HOUSING COVER TO ACT AS A BARRIER IN PLACE OF THE FAILED DISK.  COVER TO ACT AS A BARRIER IN PLACE OF THE FAILED DISK.  3. FAILED FDI DISK/CARDBOARD REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH CDC #100 DISK WHICH SECURED THE CAR.  LOCAL CONSIGNEE CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE EXCEPTIONS. TWO PLANT FOREMAN WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SPILL SITE WHERE UPON ARRIVAL APPLIED LIMESTONE ONTO THE GROUND TO NEUTRALIZE SPILLED PRODUCT.  FRED ADAMS & JIM CARPENTER OF TEXASGULF NOTIFIED.

column168: S/A, BALLANCE RECEIVED A REPORT FROM THE STOCKTON TOWER THAT TANK CAR AMOX-5500 WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVES. THE TANK CAR HAD TWO SEPARATE COMPARTMENTS. BOTH BOTTOM OUTLET VALVES WERE LEAKING. THE OUTLET VALVE ON THE "A" END WAS TIGHTENED WITH A PIPEWRENCH WHICH STOPPED THE PRODUCT FROM LEAKING. THE CONSIGNEE WAS MADE AWARE OF THE VALVE PROBLEM.

AT 2035 FLIGHT 395 RETURNED TO THE GATE AT AIRBORNE EXPRESS, PHOENIX.  THE FLIGHT CREW WAS COMPLAINING ABOUT A STRONG ODOR IN THE COCKPIT.  AFTER CHECKING THE COCKPIT THE AIRBORNE MECHANICS ON DUTY ASKED THE TERMINAL SERVICE CREW TO CHECK THE CARGO IN BELLY 1.  UPON OPENING THE BELLY CARGO DOOR WE WERE OVERCOME WITH A STRONG NAIL POLISH REMOVER LIKE SMELL.  AFTER ALLOWING THE BELLY TO AIR OUT FOR A FEW MINUTES WE WENT INTO THE BELLY TO SEARCH FOR A POSSIBLE LEAKING PACKAGE.  AFTER A FEW MOMENTS WE FOUND A SMALL (2' X 2') AREA OF FLUID ON THE FLOOR OF THE AIRCRAFT.  WE THEN TRACED THE FLUID TO AN UNMARKED BOX.  AFTER REMOVING THE BOX FROM THE AIRCRAFT WE OPENED THE BOX TO FIND THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK.  THE BOX CONTAINED ABOUT 2 GALLONS OF LAQUER & THINNER AND 3 QUARTS OF WHAT APPEARED TO BE A SOLVENT.  THE LABELS WERE WRITTEN IN SPANISH SO WE NEVER FOUND OUT WHAT THEY CONTAINED.  WE THEN CONTACTED THE AIRBORNE HAZ SUPERVISOR FOR INSTRUCTIONS ON HOW TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  WILMINGTON REMINDED US TO CALL THE FIRE DEPT AND FAA AFTER CLEANING THE AFFECTED AREA AND HAVING IT INSPECTED BY THE FIRE DEPT. THE FLIGHT WAS RELEASED.

column168: REGIONAL MANAGER DEAN WHITELEY WAS NOTIFIED THAT CONTAINER EISU 347057 LOADED ON FLATCAR TTWX 973081 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM.  CAR WAS SET OUT ON THE ROBERT SPUR AND REG. MANAGER WHITELEY ALONG WITH MCTS S. COVI AND H. RODABOUGH RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT.  INITIAL INSPECTION DETERMINED PLASTIC (POLYURETHANE) CONTAINERS APPROXIMETLY 3' X 3'.  EACH CONTAINER (TOTAL OF 16) HAD A WIRE MESH SUPPORT CAGE AND WERE PLACED ON PALLETS, SEVEN OF THE CONTAINERS WERE DOUBLE STACKED.  DRUING OFFLOADING OF THE CONTAINERS, IT WAS NOTED THAT THE TOP PALLETS HAD SHIFTED DURING MOVEMENT WHICH CRUSHED THREE OF THE BOTTOM CONTAINERS.  TWO CONTAINERS HAD PUNCTURES WHICH HAD LEAKED PRODUCT.  EISU 347057 AND TTWX 973081 WERE DECONTAIMINATED, 10 OF THE INTACT CONTAINERS WERE LOADED IN SINGLE LAYER AND FORWARDED.  TERRY AASEN OF ARCHER DANIELS MIDLAND CO. (SHIPPER) WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  HE ADVISED THAT CONTAINERS WOULD BE FORWARDED TO TRANSFER PRODUCT OF THE THREE CRUSHED CONTAINERS AND ALL REMAINING CONTAINERS (6) WILL BE RETURNED TO DECATUR, IL (SHIPPER ORIGINATION).

column168: A TRACK INSPECTOR OBSERVED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID DRIPPING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR AND REPORTED SAME TO UPRR OFFICIALS.  UPRR CORRIDOR MANAGER, MR. MIKE CABERHILL NOTIFIED MR. STAN MCINTYRE, THE MTO AT BEAUMONT, T. M. ROBINSON, REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION AT ADDIS, LOUISIANA AND PLANT PERSONNEL AT DUPONTS ORANGE, TEXAS PLANT, THE POINT OF ORIGIN. MCINTYRE WAS CONTACTED AT THE SCENE BY RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM DUPONT WHO INSPECTED THE CAR.  THIS INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAR WAS NO LONGER LEAKING, BUT HAD BEEN LEAKING FROM A DEFECTIVE EDUCTION FLANGE GASKET. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE FOR THE CAR TO BE MOVED BACK TO THE PLANT AT ORANGE FOR REPAIR.  ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE CAR WAS SECURE PRIOR TO HIS ARRIVAL AND RETURNED HOME.

SPECIAL AGENT HAZ/MAT C.E. ZERWECK WAS NOTIFIED TANK CAR PLMX 7251 WAS LEAKING FROM A WELD IN BOWL TRACK 31 AT CENTENNIAL YARD, FT. WORTH.  AGENT ZERWECK RESPONDED AND FOUND THE CAR LEAKING FROM THE WELD AT THE STUB SILL.  THE RATE WAS APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON EVERY 5 MINUTES WITH A SPRAY APPROXIMATELY 7 INCHES ACROSS LATERAL WELD.  REGIONAL DIR. CTSG STINE CONTACTED AS WAS EMTECH EMERGENCY SERVICES.  ZERWECK AND EMTRECH FORCES WERE ABLE TO TEMPORARILY STOP THE LEAK USING PETRO-PLUG, AQUA-PLUG, AND PLUG & DIKE.  WHILE THE PATCH WAS BING APPLIED, STINE CONTACTED MARK WHITE WITH MURES, THE SHIPPER, AND ADVISED HIM AS WELL AS CHEMTREC OF THE SITUATION.  THE CAR WAS MOVED FROM THE BOWL TO THE WEST END OF TRACK 301 AND THE PRODUCT TRANSFERRED TO MONTGOMERY TANK LINES TRUCKS PER MARK WHITE'S REQUEST ENROUTE TO STARTRANS TERMINAL, TEXAS CITY, TX.  THE BOWL WAS REOPENED FOR NORMAL TRAFFIC AT 1745 HOURS.  THE TRANSFER BEGAN AT 1930 AND WAS COMPLETED EXCEPT FOR 301 GALLONS AT 0130, 063093.  THE REMAINING 301 GALLONS WERE TRANSFERRED AT 1330 ON 06039.  INTO A VACCUUM TRUCK FOR LOCAL DISPOSAL PER MR. WHITE'S REQUEST.  THE TANK CAR WAS STENCILED LEAKING TANK DO NOT LOAD ON BOTH SIDES AND AN X WAS PLACED ON THE WELD AT THE B END OF THE CAR.

column168: DRIVER LYDIA JACKSON WAS MAKING A DELIVERY AT S.S.201241  ,40500 CALIF. OAKS, MURRIETA,CAL.  SHE STARTED UNLOADING HER PLUS UNLEAD AFTER CHECKING TO BE SURE THAT IT WOULD FIT AND HER OPW DOWNSPOUT WAS SECURELY FASTENED AND HER VAPOR HOSE WAS HOOKED UP PROPERLY.  SHE THEN STARTED  TO SET UP FOR HER NEXT PRODUCT WHEN SHE HEARD A HISSING NOISE.  AFTER INVESTIGATING SHE FOUND THE HISSING NOISE COMING FROM THE TANK LEVEL MONITORING SYSTEM. SHE SHUT THE FLOW OFF AT THE TRUCK AND STARTED INVESTIGATING AS TO WHY. LYDIA FIRST DISCONNECTED THE VAPOR HOSE AND PUSHED IN THE PLUNGER TO THE TANK.  THERE WERE NO VAPORS COMING OUT.  THE SIGHT GLASS AT THE TRAILER OUTLET WAS EMPTY, SO SHE THEN UNLATCHED AND LIFTED THE OPW FROM THE FILL STEM. AS SHE LIFTED THE OPW THE BACK PRESSURE IN THE TANK WAS SO GREAT IT SHOT THE GAS ABOUT 3 FEET INTO THE AIR AND SOCKING HER.  LYDIA TRIED TO GET THE OPW BACK ON THE FILL STEM BUT COULD'NT BECAUSE OF THE BACK PRESSURE.  AFTER APPROX. A MINUTE THE PRESSURE LESSENED ENOUGH TO GET THE OPW BACK ON.  LYDIA HAD THE STATION ATTENDANT CALL 911 THEN PROCEEDED TO CONE OFF THE AREA AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  SHE THEN CALLED TERMINAL SUPV. DONNIE MATHESON WHO WENT TO MURRIETA.  WHEN HE ARRIVED BOTH FIRE AND POLICE DEPT. WERE THERE.  THE STATION MANAGER WAS CALLED BUT DECLINED TO COME TO THE SCENE.

THE SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING BY SORT SUPERVISOR MIKE BALLEIN.  THE SHIPMENT WAS A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH NO HAZARD MARKINGS, LABELS, OR ORIENTAION.  THERE WAS NO SHIPPER'S CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THE SHIPMENT. INSIDE THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX WERE 4 BOXES OF EYEGLASS LENSES, 1 PILLOW BLOCK, 4 YARN BUFFING WHEELS, AND 3 BOTTLES OF QUICK CLEAN LENS CLEANER.  THE BOTTLES OF LENS CLEANER WERE PLASTIC BOTTLES WITH PUMP SPRAY CAPS, 8 OZ. CAPACITY (EACH), AND HAD NFPA RATINGS OF HEALTH-1, FLAMMABILITY-3, AND REACTIVITY 0. THE SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD IN OUR HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY AND WILL BE FORWARDED TO DESTINATION UPON RELEASE BY THE FAA AND OBTAINING PROPER CERTIFICATION FROM THE SHIPPER.

column168: ON 6-12-93 AT APPROXIMATELY 0335 HRS., I, KAREN NICKOLS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DR, WILMINGTON, OH 45177 INVESTIGATED A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN OUR SORT FACILITY.  THE LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED BY ANDY HOLMES/SORT SUPERVISOR WHO REPORTED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS CLEAR LIQUID WITH A STRONG ODOR AND ONE EMPLOYEE HAD COME IN CONTACT WITH IT.  UPON ARIVAL TO THE SCENE (PRIMARY "B" DIVERTER 21 IN OUR SORT FACILITY), MY RESPONSE UNIT PARTNER (JAMES GILLIAM/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN) AND I DONED ORGANIC VAPOR/ACID GAS CARTRIDGE MASKES TO PROTECT OURSELVES FROM THE ODOR.  WE TESTED THE LIQUID WITH PH PAPER. THE PAPER GAVE NO INDICATION OF PH.  WE TESTED THE LIQUID WITH WATER TEST PAPER WHICH ALSO GAVE NO INDICATION OF WATER BASE.  WE BEGAN REMOVING BOXES FROM THE AREA (SEVERAL BOXES WERE LEAKED UPON AND CONTAMINATED) TO TRY TO FIND THE LEAKING SHIPMENT.  THE SECOND SHIPMENT THAT WE INSPECTED WAS THE SOURCE OF THE PRODUCT SPILLED.  THE LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS 2 FIBERBOARD BOXES BOUND TOGETHER WITH BUBBLE WRAP AND CLEAR PACKAGING TAPE. WE CUT THEM APART AND OPENED THE TOP BOX.  THE OUTER BOX WAS WHITE FIBERBOARD WITH NO  MARKINGS OR LABELS. THERE WERE NO ORIENTATION MARKINGS ON IT.  INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WE FOUND 12 X 6 OZ. PLASTIC BOTTLES WITH PLASTIC SCREW-TYPE CLOSURES.  EACH PLASTIC BOTTLE HAD APPROXIMATELY 6 OZ. OF LIQUID IN THEM.  EACH BOTTLE HAD A NUMBER AND A LETTER MARKED ON IT WITH MARKER.  THESE MARKINGS WERE VERY LIGHT AND DIFFICULT IF NOT IMPOSSIBLE TO READ.  NONE OF THE PLASTIC BOTTLES IN THIS FIBERBOARD BOX WERE LEAKING, HOWEVER, THIS FIBERBOARD BOX WAS SECURED TO THE SECOND FIBERBOARD BOX AGAINST THE ORIENTATION OF THE INNER RECEPTACLES.  THERE WAS A PLASTIC BAG USED FOR PACKING MATERIAL STUFFED INSIDE AROUND THE PLASTIC BOTTLES.  THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX WAS MANUFACTURED BY MILLER CONTAINER CORPORATION IN ROCK ISLAND, IL.  THE SECOND OR BOTTOM FIBERBOARD BOX WAS ALSO WHITE WITH NO LABELS.  THERE WAS THE MARKING "X - F MER FLUID" WRITTEN ON THE SIDE OF IT IN BLACK MARKER.  THERE WERE NO ORIENTATION MARKINGS ON THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  ALL OF THE INNER RECEPTACLES WERE PROPERLY ORIENTATED IN THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  INSIDE WE FOUND 3 X 8 OZ CLEAR, GLSS JARS WITH PLASTIC SCREW-TYPE CLOSURES.  ALL THREE WERE MARKED "CONTAMINATED PCB OIL".  1 X "SAMPLE #1, 1 X "SAMPLE #2, 1 X "SAMPLE #4. ALL DATED MARCH 1993.  ALSO INSIDE, THREE 2 X 1 QT. CLEAR, GLASS JARS WITH PLASTIC SCREW-TYPE CLOSURES.  1 STATED "F-5 JIM JONES COOL-ADE MIX", 1 SATED "F-2 4-7-93 12:01 P.M." ALSO, 4 X 8 OZ BROWN GLASS BOTTLES WITH PLASTIC SCREW-TYPE CLOSURES.  1 X "SAMPLES OF TRANSFORMER LIQID 37 PPM:, 2 X "SAMPLES OF TRANSFORMER LIQUID".  THERE WAS 1 X 4 OZ. PLASTIC BOTTLE WITH PLASTIC SCREW-TYPE CLOSURE WITH "SPARE" WRITTEN ON IT IN MARKER. THIS PLASTIC BOTTLE WAS THEN INSIDE A FIBERBOARD TUBE THAT WAS NOT TAPED SHUT. THIS FIBERBOARD BOX WAS MARKED "PAINT, UN1263" AND THERE WAS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABEL ON IT.  UPON OPENING THE FIBERBOARD BOX INSIDE WE FOUND 4 2-QUART PLASTIC RECEPTICLES.  THERE WERE STYROFOAM PEANUTS AROUND THE PLASTIC RECEPTICLES.  THE PLASTIC RECEPTICLES HAD SCREW-TYPE CLOSURES WITH TAPE TO SECURE THE CLOSURES.  THERE WAS NOT ENOUGH ROOM FOR OUTAGE.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED, AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED ON TO ITS DESTINATION.

DOCKMAN, AL COOK, WAS LOADING THE SHIPMENT INTO DOOR 34, WHEN HE DORPPED ONE (1) CARTON CAUSING A JAR INSIDE TO BREAK OPEN.  THE CONTENTS OF THE JAR LEAKED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  MR. JIM COOPER OF CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION ON HOW TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP PROCESS.  I RECOMMEND BETTER INNER PACKAGING TO PREVENT FURTHER INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE.

DRIVER SALES REPRESENTATIVE WAS UNLOADING TRAILER-IN SLIDING BLADE OF 2 WHEELED CART UNDER THE DRUM IN QUESTION, HE PUNCTURED THE DRUM. SERVICE CENTER MANAGER WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED, AND THE AREA WASSECURED.  SCM REFERRED TO THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE, AND OPENED DOCK DOOR FOR VENTILATION.  SCM THEN CALLED CHEMTREC AND SPOKE WITH JOE DEBNAM, WHO ADVISED THAT KML WAS A MEMBER FIRM, AND THAT SOMEONE FROM KML WOULD CALL ME WITHIN 1/2 HOUR.  PAUL MILLS OF KML CALLED WITH THE 1/2 HOUR AND WE DISCUSSED THE SPILL.  AFTER ASCERTAINING WHICH PRODUCT WAS SPILLED, HE ADVISED THAT WE COULD CLEAN UP THE ABSORBENT PREVESIOULY PUT DOWN TO CONTAIN, AND THAT WE COULD NEURALIZE THE REMAINING WITH A 1:1 SOLUTION OF WATER AND VINEGAR.  HE FURTHER ADVISED TO PLACE THE DRUM, UPSIDE DOWN, IN RECOVERY DRUM WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM, AND RETURN TO SHIPPER FOR RECOVERY.
column172: Reusable molded polyethylene container without overpack RHNA*

column168: TERMINAL MGR AT NEW ORLEANS ADVISED THAT TANK CAR WAS VENTING VAPORS FROM TOP ON INTERCHANGE TRACK THERE WAS A CLOUD OVER THE CAR AND A LOCAL FOREMAN REPORTED IT TO FIRE DEPT. FIRE DEPT. POLICE DEPT AND ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY RESPONDED.  ATTEMPTED TO CONTACTED SHIPPER BUT WAS UNABLE TO REACH.  CSXT HIRED EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, REIDEL PETERSON TO RESPOND.  REIDEL FOUND THAT LIQUID LOADING PIPE WAS LOOSE AT THE FLANGE WHERE IT ATTACHED TO THE TANK.   BOLTS ON FLANGED WERE TIGHTENED DOWN AND VAPOR RELEASE WAS STOPPED.

A SWITCHMAN REPORTED A TANK CAR THAT SLOSHED PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED AT CSXT RAIL YARD IN NEW ORLEANS, LA.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC MR ED ERNEWEIN BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, RESPONDED ON BEHALF OF CSXT.  HE FOUND THE CAR HAD A BAD MANWAY LID GASKET.  ERNEWEIN CONTRACTED THE CONSIGNEE WHO WAS NEARBY.  THE CONSIGNEE RESPONDED AND USING TEFLON GASKETING MATERAIL FORMED A NEW GASKET.  THE MANWAY WAS SECURED AND THE CAR WAS SHAKEN TO INSURE THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE BEFORE IT WAS RELEASED.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings; Vent
column168: D.C. COOPER, MANAGER, CTS, WAS NOTIFIED BY W.L. MILTON, MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, THAT TANK CAR KCCX 2430 WAS NOTED LEAKING BY R.J. KELLY, RAILROAD SAFETY INSPECTOR, HAZMAT, U.S. DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION, FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION.  CAR WAS NOTED UPON ARRIVAL AT LAS VEGAS MOVING IN TRAIN CYR 15, WHICH WAS SET OUT AT ARDEN, NEVADA, AND ISOLATED AT THE CABOOSE TRACK PENDING INSPECTION.  INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE RUPTURE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT HAD BURST.  THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD MIDLAND BAFFLE STYLE, WAS DISASSEMBLED, AND THE BURST RUPTURE DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE 100 POUND STAINLESSTEEL TEFLON BSB DISC.  THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED AND THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE PROPERLY SECURED.  CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CEMTREC, MR BILL GASSON, REPORTED NUMBER 22614; KENNECOTT UTAH COPPER, MR. STAN ANDERSON; NEVADA DIVISION OF EMERGNECY MANAGEMENT, MS. SUSAN MOORE, INCIDENT NUMBER H930616F; CLARK COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT EMERGENCY DISPATCH (NO RESPONSE REQUIRED, VERBAL ACKNOWLEDGEMENT); NEVADA PUBLIC SERVICE COMMISSION, MR. JERRY CHRIST.

A CARTON WAS FOUND LEAKING UPON ARRIVAL AND WAS ISOLATED IN THE HAZMAT BAY.  THE CARTON WAS PROPERLY RECOOPERED AND OVERPACKED INTO A NEW DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM, WITH PROPER MARKINGSAND LABELS APPLIED.  THE TRAILER WAS CHECKED FOR SPILLAGE AND NONE WAS FOUND.  THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

CUSTOMER WAS CARRYING FOUR PLASTIC BOTTLES OF POOL CLEANER IN HIS CARRY ON LUGGAGE.  WHEN TRANSFERRING IN PHEONIX, HE TURNED HIS BAG ON THE SIDE AND THE LIQUID FROM ONE BOTTLE SPILLED INTO THE OVERHEAD BIN.  THE ITEMS WERE NOT DECLARED OR PROPERLY PACKAGE FOR TRANSPORTATION.
column172: Plastic bottle, capacity 2 gallons or less

column168: RECEIVED HAZMAT FREIGHT FROM DELTA AIRLINES TOTAL OF 4 CARTONS WITH ONE BOX DAMAGED AND LEAKING.  AS SOON AS IT WAS BROUGHT TO MY ATTENTION I CALLED ON THE AIRBORNE HAZMAT DESK AND INITIATED THE SPILL RESPONSE PROCEDURES AT 2135 I RECEIVED A CALL BACK FROM TOM TARGET OUR HAZMAT SPECIALIST AND HE AGAIN WENT OVER SPILL RESPONSE PROCEDURES AND ADVISED THAT IF ANYONE NEEDED MEDICAL ATTENTION TO IMMEDIATELY SEEK PREFESSIONAL HELP.  HE THEN CALLED SHIPPER TO OBTAIN THE MSDS AND HAD THAT FAXED TO US AT THE EARLIST POSSIBLE MOMENT.  THE BOX WAS SECLUDED AND KEPT AWAY FROM OTHER HAZMAT MATERIAL AND SHIPPER AND SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED TO HAVE PERSONNEL COME BY TO PICK IT UP.  HAZMAT INCIDENT REPORT WAS THE FILLED OUT AND FORWARDED TO APPROPRIATE PARTIES.
DSR SCOTT LOVE WAS LOADING FRIEGHT INTO TRAILER #463-0025 AND HIT THE DRUM WHICH WAS ALREADY LOADED.  HE WAS ON FORKLIFT # 466-2029.
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column168: PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN PRIMARY SORT.  ONE OF ONE FIVE GALLON BUCKETS HAD A LOOSE CAP.  THE COMPLETE PACKAGE WAS REPACKAGED & SENT ON. THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZMAT PROCEDURES.

column42: HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S. OR ORM-E, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: CARMEN R.A. KOEING, JR. WAS INSPECTING 14 CARS ON TRACK 50 IN MANSFIELD YARD WHEN HE NOTICED "A WHITE POWDERY SUBSTANCE, SOME AREAS COVERED IN A GREEN SEMI-PASTE MATERIAL, AND DARK GREEN LIQUID DRIPPING FROM VARIOS POINTS OF THE UNDERCARRIAGE OF "MPA 39706.  HE FELT A BURNIN SENSATION ON HIS FACE AND EYES; HE REPORTED THE INCIDENT AND FLUSHED HIS FACE AND EYES. ROAD FOREMAN CATTRELL TOOK KOEING TO MANSFIELD GENERAL HOSPITAL WHERE HE WAS TREATED BY DR. GINSBERG AND RELEASED.  CONRAIL SUMMONED CONTRACTER O.H. MATERIALS TO CONTAIN ANY SPILL; O.H.M. REPORTED ALL BARS WERE INTACT.  THE FLOOR, HOWEVER, WAS COVERED WITH MATERIAL THAT HAS SIFTED THROUGH THE NAILABLE FLOOR.  SINCE CAR WAS IN INTERCHANGE, CONRAIL REJECTED CAR, INFORMED ASHLAND RAILWAY TO PICK UP AND RETURN TO SHIPPER.

CARMEN WERE INSPECTING CARS IN SELKIRK YARD ON JUNE 29TH WHEN THEY DISCOVERED RAIX 705 LEAKING AT 1115 HOURS.  CONRAIL, VIA CHEMTREE, CONTACTED THE SHIPPER WHO, IN TURN, ARRAGNED FOR PRAXAIR TO SEND J. SYROMI.  HE TIGHTENED THE #10 (POWELL) GLOBE VALVE AND RELEASED THE CAR.
ROUGHT TO ME BY INCOM-PERSON DAMAGE INSPECTION REPORT & MALLINCKRODT (DMN) COMPLETED.  BALANCE OF CONTENTS SENT ON FOR DELIVERY.

US DOT, FRA INSPECTOR K. GILMORE, ON JUNE 18H AT 0930, DISCOVERED A RUPTURED DISK ON CAR KCCX 2513 WHITEL IT WAS ON TRACK 11 OF THE RECEIVING YARD AT AVON.  CONRAIL CONTACTED CHEMTREC WHO, IT TURN, CONTACTED THE SHIPPER.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE R W STOCK ARRANGED FOR REPLACEMENT OF THE DISK.  THE CAR WAS THEN UNLOADED AND CONRAIL'S FLEXI-FLO SITE IN AVON YARD.

ON THRUSDAY 6/24/93 @ 2345 A CO-PILOT FOR RYAN INT'L, WHILE OPENING THE CARGO DOOR, COMPLAINED OF VAPORS COMING FROM THE CARGO AREA OF THE AIRCRAFT.  SHE COMPLAINED OF DIZZINESS AND FELT LIGHTHEADED DUE TO THE VAPORS.  BECAUSE OF THE SITUATION, THE MIAMI FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE.  CONTAINER 0007 WAS DESIGNATED AS THE CONTAINER IN WHICH THE VAPORS WERE COMING FROM. THE CONTAINER WAS UNLOADED AND A BOX OF LIQUID NAIL (ETHYL METHACRYLATE) WAS FOUND TO HAVE LEAKED OUT.  THE BOX WAS CONTAINED AND TURNED OVER TO THE UNITED STATES POSTAL SERVICE.  THE POSTAL SERVICE, BECAUSE AN INDIVIDUAL WAS EXPOSED TO THE PRODUCT, HAD THE CONTENTS TESTED. THE RESULTS STATED THE PRODUCT IN QUESTION WAS A LIQUID NAIL HARDENER.  THE UNTED STATES POSTAL SERVICE AND MYSELF HAVE OR WILL BE IN CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER EXPLAINING THE PROPER SHIPPING REQUIREMENTS AND POCEDURE WHEN SHIPPING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  BEN VIDE, UNITED STATES POSAL SERVICE MANAGER IN MIAMI, IS THE PERSON WHO HANDLED THE INCIDENT FROM THE POSTAL SERVICE.

column168: GASOLINE-DRIVEN ENGINE PACKED IN WOODEN BOX.  NO MARKINGS/LABELS INDICATING DANGEROUS GOODS. ENGINE APPARENTLY WAS NOT COMPLETELY DRAINED & TOP WAS NOT TIGHTLY CLOSED. A SMALL AMOUNT OF GASOLINE LEAKED OUT, AND THE ENGINE WAS DISCOVERED WHEN THE  BOX WAS OPENED.  THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF THE SITUATION. THE FAA WAS CONTACTED & THE PACKAGE WAS HELD FOR INSPECTION.

column168: THE PACKAGE WAS BEING UNLOADED AND TIPPED TO THE RIGHT SIDE. THE GASOLINE THAT HAD REMAINED IN THE LINES OF THE ENGINE SPILLED ONTO THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  UPON NOTICING THE GAS AROMA.  THE PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM THE SORT. THE MSP RAMP NOTIFIED FEDERAL EXPRESS DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRAITION. THE FAA MSP CASFO WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY HAVE INVESTIGATED. & RELEASED THE PACKAGE.  THE SHIPPER HAS PICKED UP THE PACKAGE.

ON 06-29-93 WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. CECIL HARRIS, CAR FORMAN AT ELKO, REGARDING TANKCAR KCCX2419.  MR HARRIS REPORTED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP AND THAT IT HAD BEEN SET OUT FOR REPAIR.  UPON ARRIVAL AT ELKO ON 06-30-93 AT 0800 HOURS, THE TANK CAR WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO HAVE A FAILED RUPTURE DISC.  IT WAS REPLACED WITH A BS&B 100 PSI DISC AND THE CAR WAS DECONTAMINATED WITH WATER AND SODIBICARBONATE.  ALL REPAIRS AND CLEANUP COMPLETE AT 1030 HOURS.  SAME DATE AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE SHIPMENT, WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.
